      %h2
        Q. How do the previews work?
      %p
        A. Dubsar's views reflect the structure of WordNet&reg;, but often, in previous
        versions, you would have to tap through a couple of empty views in order to get
        to the information you wanted. That's because the Search and Word views are just
        lists of things: search results and word senses. Now Dubsar shows you a preview
        of the following view for the first item in each list.
      %p
        For example, search for onomatopoeia. You'll get back a view like this:
 
      =image_tag 'onomatopoeia-1.png', :size => '240x426'

      %p
        This view includes a preview. To hide the preview, tap the Hide button at the
        right of the bottom toolbar. When the preview goes away, you'll see this:

      =image_tag 'onomatopoeia-2.png', :size => '240x426'

      %p
        This was previously the only content of this Search view. Having found
        the one word matching your search, you had to tap ahead to the Word view in
        order to see more. Now you'll see this in the Word view:

      =image_tag 'onomatopoeia-3.png', :size => '240x426'

      %p
        Again, this view contains a preview. If you tap Hide again, you'll see:

      =image_tag 'onomatopoeia-4.png', :size => '240x426'

      %p
        Before the introduction of previews, this was all you'd see in this Word view,
        a single sense. Tapping once again on that row, you'll finally come to the
        Sense view:

      =image_tag 'onomatopoeia-5.png', :size => '240x426'

      %p
        This is just what was previewed in the previous two views, but you didn't have
        to tap through two empty views to see this information, as you did in Dubsar
        1.1.1 and earlier. Note that in the Search view, you get a preview of the first
        Word view in the search results, and that preview in turn includes a preview
        of the first Sense in that Word view, just as you see in the full Word view if
        you tap on the first row of the search results.

      %p
        Sometimes you are interested in a long list. Search for something like
        %em take.
        If you hide the preview in the search view, you'll see many matches. Take is
        primarily a verb, so 
        =link_to 'take (v.)', 'dubsar:///words/145841'
        has a higher frequency count than other parts of speech and is displayed as
        the first result. (Search results are displayed with exact matches at the top,
        followed by fulltext matches. Exact matches, if there is more than one, are
        sorted by frequency count.) But maybe you're interested in
        =link_to 'take (n.)', 'dubsar:///words/32773'
        or one of the other matches. Hide the preview to see them. Similarly in the
        Word view, you can always hide the preview to show the rest of the senses of
        the word.
